1
00:00:54,950 --> 00:00:56,950
Hello, boys!

2
00:03:34,910 --> 00:03:36,950
* Dee dee *

3
00:03:46,590 --> 00:03:48,590
* Bom-bom, bom-bom *

4
00:03:48,670 --> 00:03:51,230
* Bom-bom ba-bom-doo *

5
00:03:55,390 --> 00:03:57,350
* Bom-bom bom-boom-bom **

6
00:04:14,430 --> 00:04:16,630
Hey, Yaskov. How are ya?

7
00:04:16,670 --> 00:04:21,190
Kendig.
What an unexpected pleasure.

8
00:04:22,550 --> 00:04:25,590
- May I have it, please?
- Have what?

9
00:04:25,670 --> 00:04:28,790
I got it all on film, Yaskov.

10
00:04:28,870 --> 00:04:30,910
You don't wanna deal
with the West Germans.

11
00:04:30,990 --> 00:04:33,030
They don't like Russian
Intelligence. You know that.

12
00:04:33,110 --> 00:04:35,150
Give it to me,
and we'll forget about it.

13
00:04:35,230 --> 00:04:37,830
I could make a run for it.

14
00:04:37,910 --> 00:04:40,870
Come on, Yaskov.
You running, me chasing you?

15
00:04:40,950 --> 00:04:43,310
We'd look like
Laurel and Hardy.

16
00:04:43,390 --> 00:04:45,350
Two clowns, huh?

17
00:04:47,030 --> 00:04:49,430
You're a good man, Kendig,
the best they've got.

18
00:04:50,670 --> 00:04:53,230
- I wish you were with us.
- Thanks, Yaskov.

19
00:04:53,270 --> 00:04:55,270
Da Svidaniya.

20
00:05:05,270 --> 00:05:10,030
Lufthansa flight 22
arriving at gate 17.

21
00:05:19,230 --> 00:05:24,030
Passenger Bernstein,
please go to the courtesy phone.

22
00:05:24,110 --> 00:05:27,230
I didn't expect to be met, Joe.
What's the matter?

23
00:05:27,310 --> 00:05:31,470
Myerson's in a sweat
because you let that Russian go.

24
00:05:31,510 --> 00:05:33,910
He's talking about
the Russians in Cuba again.

25
00:05:33,990 --> 00:05:35,910
Talking about
sending you to Cuba.

26
00:05:35,990 --> 00:05:38,950
- Oh.
- That's why you got the chopper.

27
00:05:45,350 --> 00:05:47,270
- Hi, Wanda.
- Good morning.

28
00:05:47,350 --> 00:05:49,270
- How are ya?
- Welcome back.

29
00:05:49,350 --> 00:05:51,590
Hi, Edie. Hi, Sherri.

30
00:05:51,630 --> 00:05:54,310
- Beverly, how are you?
- Good morning, Mr. Kendig.

31
00:05:54,390 --> 00:05:58,470
In here, Kendig. Cutter, stay put.
I want to see you after this.

32
00:06:02,670 --> 00:06:05,710
Hi, Myerson.
I thought you were taller.

33
00:06:05,790 --> 00:06:08,590
I don't remember you being this short.
How'd you get so short?

34
00:06:08,670 --> 00:06:10,670
Up yours, Kendig.

35
00:06:13,950 --> 00:06:15,910
Where's your report?
You haven't filed it.

36
00:06:15,990 --> 00:06:18,910
I just got off the airplane.
The job's finished. What's the hurry?

37
00:06:18,990 --> 00:06:23,870
Typical. It's difficult
growing up, isn't it?

38
00:06:23,950 --> 00:06:26,470
Aren't you just a little senior...

39
00:06:26,550 --> 00:06:29,390
to be shadowing people around
the streets of Munich personally?

40
00:06:29,470 --> 00:06:32,310
I worked on thatjob
for two years.

41
00:06:32,390 --> 00:06:34,430
I had a right
to be in at the finish.

42
00:06:34,510 --> 00:06:36,590
You mind ifl sit down?

43
00:06:36,670 --> 00:06:38,750
The object, Kendig,
was to dismantle...

44
00:06:38,830 --> 00:06:41,470
the Russian network over there.

45
00:06:41,550 --> 00:06:43,990
All you did was
nab a few small fry...

46
00:06:44,070 --> 00:06:45,990
three clerks
and a cleaning woman.

47
00:06:46,070 --> 00:06:49,550
And they blew the whistle on the others.
We got the whole kit and caboodle.

48
00:06:49,630 --> 00:06:51,670
We plugged that leakfor good.

49
00:06:51,750 --> 00:06:54,350
-What about Yaskov?
- What about Yaskov?

50
00:06:54,390 --> 00:06:56,350
What'd you want me to do,
terminate him?

51
00:06:56,430 --> 00:06:58,990
Is that the way you did things
in your dirty tricks division?

52
00:06:59,070 --> 00:07:01,270
You're too new in this section
to go jumping to conclusions.

53
00:07:01,350 --> 00:07:03,350
Excuse me.

54
00:07:03,430 --> 00:07:05,910
- I never intended...
- Get my wife, please.

55
00:07:05,990 --> 00:07:08,910
I never intended
to arrest Yas...

56
00:07:08,990 --> 00:07:11,750
- Go ahead.
- I never intended to arrest...

57
00:07:11,830 --> 00:07:14,230
Hello, darling.
Beverly tells me you called.

58
00:07:14,310 --> 00:07:17,110
Yes, dear. It's about
the dinner party this evening.

59
00:07:17,190 --> 00:07:19,350
I wanted to make quite certain
you hadn't forgotten.

60
00:07:19,430 --> 00:07:22,270
Oh, no. I haven't forgotten.

61
00:07:22,350 --> 00:07:24,270
- You're a good boy.
- Thank you.

62
00:07:24,350 --> 00:07:26,430
- There's one other thing... the house.
- What about the house?

63
00:07:26,510 --> 00:07:29,990
- Do we really have to go
down there this summer?

64
00:07:30,070 --> 00:07:33,870
If you don't want to go, we just
won't go. It's your decision.

65
00:07:35,950 --> 00:07:37,950
Decisions, decisions. Why do I
find it so hard to make up my mind?

66
00:07:38,030 --> 00:07:40,070
Excuse me. Excuse me.

67
00:07:40,150 --> 00:07:42,270
- Hello? Hello?
- Don't do that?

68
00:07:42,350 --> 00:07:45,990
- Can you hear me?
- Yes, dear, I can hear you.

69
00:07:46,070 --> 00:07:47,990
Now listen. Just call
that real estate dame...

70
00:07:48,070 --> 00:07:50,070
and tell her to rent it out.

71
00:07:50,150 --> 00:07:53,950
- Yes, dear, immediately.
- Tell her no kids, no pets, no Democrats.

72
00:07:53,990 --> 00:07:56,390
Yes, dear.
Oh, one last thing.

73
00:07:56,470 --> 00:07:59,550
The dinner is formal. I called
Mrs. Blandforth to make certain.

74
00:07:59,590 --> 00:08:01,990
Good. I can wear
my new tuxedo.

75
00:08:02,070 --> 00:08:05,270
- Good-bye, darling.
- Good-bye, dear.

76
00:08:05,350 --> 00:08:08,590
- May I say something now?
- We've got a house near Savannah.

77
00:08:08,630 --> 00:08:10,870
She won't give it up.
Says it's close to her mother.

78
00:08:10,950 --> 00:08:12,870
She never wants
to use it though.

79
00:08:12,950 --> 00:08:17,670
I never intended to arrest Yaskov.
I wanted him to stay right where he is.

80
00:08:17,710 --> 00:08:19,710
You wanted.

81
00:08:19,790 --> 00:08:22,350
Yes, I wanted.

82
00:08:22,430 --> 00:08:25,310
I've know the man for 20 years. I
know how he thinks. I know how he acts.

83
00:08:25,350 --> 00:08:27,750
We take him out,
they put another man in.

84
00:08:27,830 --> 00:08:29,790
It takes us six months
to find out who.

85
00:08:29,870 --> 00:08:31,950
It takes us another year and a half
to learn his style.

86
00:08:32,030 --> 00:08:35,670
There are Russian combat troops
90 miles off our shore.

87
00:08:35,750 --> 00:08:39,710
You had the head ofthe entire
K. G. B. for western Europe...

88
00:08:39,790 --> 00:08:41,910
in your hand,
and you let him go.

89
00:08:41,990 --> 00:08:43,990
That's the bottom line, isn't it?

90
00:08:44,070 --> 00:08:48,630
I don't even begin to understand
the relevancy of that.

91
00:08:48,710 --> 00:08:52,870
- It's my station.
- It's not your station! It's our station!

92
00:08:52,950 --> 00:08:55,150
You should've learned
that one a long time ago.

93
00:08:55,230 --> 00:08:57,270
You weren't there
to make policy.

94
00:08:57,350 --> 00:08:59,710
You were there
to carry out policy.

95
00:08:59,750 --> 00:09:03,710
Now we've had your history
of making up your own rules...

96
00:09:03,790 --> 00:09:06,030
under review
for some time now.

97
00:09:07,590 --> 00:09:10,750
We're reassigning you, Kendig.

98
00:09:10,830 --> 00:09:13,390
You're going to sweat out
your time until pension...

99
00:09:13,430 --> 00:09:16,510
running the filing section
right here.

100
00:09:16,590 --> 00:09:20,470
Come on, Myerson. I'm a field man.
I've always been a field man.

101
00:09:20,510 --> 00:09:24,310
The good news is I'm putting your
friend Joe Cutter in your place.

102
00:09:24,390 --> 00:09:26,310
-Joe Cutter's a very good man.
- Yes, he is.

103
00:09:26,390 --> 00:09:28,430
And he's 20 years
younger than you are.

104
00:09:28,510 --> 00:09:32,070
Twenty-one. I don't know what's
buggin' you. You're overreacting.

105
00:09:32,150 --> 00:09:35,710
I don't believe you're this upset
because ofthat Russian in Munich.

106
00:09:35,790 --> 00:09:39,150
Damn it. I hate a man who doesn't
know when the party is over.

107
00:09:39,190 --> 00:09:41,750
You will get that report
together, won't you?

108
00:09:41,830 --> 00:09:44,510
And you can file it yourself
Monday morning.

109
00:09:46,190 --> 00:09:48,790
Is this some kind ofa joke,
Myerson?

110
00:09:48,870 --> 00:09:50,950
Come in, Cutter.

111
00:09:53,590 --> 00:09:56,950
Congratulations, Joe.
You just got yourself a new job.

112
00:10:26,470 --> 00:10:28,430
- How ya doin', Alex?
- Fine, Kendig.

113
00:10:28,510 --> 00:10:30,470
Did you have the Redkskins
last Sunday?

114
00:10:30,510 --> 00:10:32,990
- You bet I did.
- Good. I'm gonna look at the Kinberg file.

115
00:10:33,070 --> 00:10:35,510
You know where it's at.

116
00:11:07,430 --> 00:11:09,430
Okay, Alex.

117
00:11:10,550 --> 00:11:12,470
Just stick with us this Sunday.

118
00:11:12,550 --> 00:11:14,550
- We're gonna slaughter the Cowboys.
- I'm with you.

119
00:11:34,070 --> 00:11:37,270
Mr. Myerson?
He's still not in his office.

120
00:11:37,350 --> 00:11:39,590
He hasn't checked in
for two days, sir.

121
00:11:39,670 --> 00:11:42,670
- Anything else?
- His apartment phone doesn't answer...

122
00:11:42,750 --> 00:11:46,550
but, before he left, he put in
a call to Salzburg, Austria.

123
00:11:46,630 --> 00:11:48,790
- Check it out.
- Yes, sir.

124
00:12:12,950 --> 00:12:14,950
Excuse me.

125
00:12:15,030 --> 00:12:17,350
I seeyou're looking
at the wine list.

126
00:12:17,430 --> 00:12:21,510
-Yes, I am.
- May I perhaps suggest a wine?

127
00:12:21,590 --> 00:12:23,350
That would be nice.

128
00:12:23,430 --> 00:12:25,750
May I sit down, please?

129
00:12:25,790 --> 00:12:27,790
Yes. Please do.

130
00:12:29,510 --> 00:12:32,310
What wine do you
feel like drinking?

131
00:12:32,390 --> 00:12:35,950
I'm not sure. I, uh...

132
00:12:36,030 --> 00:12:37,950
Um, just a good wine.

133
00:12:38,030 --> 00:12:41,710
What wine do you prefer?
Red wine? White? French? German?

134
00:12:43,310 --> 00:12:46,070
I don't know. What's good
for this time ofthe day?

135
00:12:46,110 --> 00:12:49,990
That would depend on what
you're thinking of eating.

136
00:12:51,670 --> 00:12:55,070
Well, frankly, I... I, um...

137
00:12:55,150 --> 00:12:57,990
hadn't quite made a decision
as to my meal.

138
00:12:58,070 --> 00:13:01,550
- Is wine that important?
- Very important.

139
00:13:01,630 --> 00:13:04,910
Do you prefer young wine
or one slightly older?

140
00:13:04,990 --> 00:13:06,950
Oh, slightly... slightly older.

141
00:13:07,030 --> 00:13:10,470
Mm. As a general rule,
the older wines are better.

142
00:13:10,550 --> 00:13:14,030
It takes time forthe elements
in wine to resolve themselves...

143
00:13:14,110 --> 00:13:16,070
into an harmonious whole.

144
00:13:16,110 --> 00:13:18,710
It takes time and oxygen.

145
00:13:20,310 --> 00:13:24,030
- Are you serious?
- Deadly serious.

146
00:13:24,110 --> 00:13:26,430
Wine is not
a disembodied essence.

147
00:13:26,510 --> 00:13:30,110
It is the product of skill,
knowledge and, in many cases, love.

148
00:13:32,550 --> 00:13:35,630
Are you a...
a wine salesperson?

149
00:13:35,710 --> 00:13:37,750
No. I am an ordinary person...

150
00:13:37,830 --> 00:13:40,230
living quietly on
the generous endowment...

151
00:13:40,310 --> 00:13:42,870
left me by my dear
departed husband.

152
00:13:42,950 --> 00:13:44,870
- Oh, that's wonderful.
- Thank you.

153
00:13:44,950 --> 00:13:47,990
- You certainly know a lot about wines.
- You're American.

154
00:13:48,070 --> 00:13:51,270
- Yes.
- Americans hold many myths about wine.

155
00:13:51,350 --> 00:13:54,670
You are all interested in fitness,
in general health.

156
00:13:54,710 --> 00:13:57,670
You think wine is bad
for your liver and your heart.

157
00:13:57,750 --> 00:14:01,350
This is completely not true.

158
00:14:01,430 --> 00:14:05,030
It is the drinking of wine that makes
it possible to eat the rich food...

159
00:14:05,110 --> 00:14:07,110
which is bad for your liver
and your heart...

160
00:14:07,190 --> 00:14:09,790
because wine cuts grease.

161
00:14:09,870 --> 00:14:13,070
A sip of wine leaves
your mouth completely clean...

162
00:14:13,150 --> 00:14:15,190
and ready for the next bite...

163
00:14:15,270 --> 00:14:18,310
of whatever it is you're eating.

164
00:14:24,630 --> 00:14:28,310
Oh, where have you been,
you old goat?

165
00:14:28,390 --> 00:14:30,790
You bastard. I thought
I'd never see you again.

166
00:14:30,870 --> 00:14:33,750
Please watch your language.
You know how sensitive I am.

167
00:14:33,830 --> 00:14:36,070
Come home with me.
I'll give you lunch.

168
00:14:36,150 --> 00:14:38,110
This is a terrible place to eat.

169
00:14:46,230 --> 00:14:48,150
Does he bite?

170
00:14:48,230 --> 00:14:50,550
Only people he doesn't like.

171
00:14:50,630 --> 00:14:53,070
Oh. I only bite people I like.

172
00:14:54,390 --> 00:14:56,390
Hey, it's nice.

173
00:14:57,590 --> 00:15:00,230
- How many hectares do you have?
- Two.

174
00:15:06,990 --> 00:15:08,990
Nice.

175
00:15:10,830 --> 00:15:13,030
Ah. Very nice indeed.

176
00:15:13,110 --> 00:15:15,750
Thank you.
There's more.

177
00:15:22,950 --> 00:15:25,190
- Hey, magnificent.
- Thank you.

178
00:15:25,270 --> 00:15:27,190
Do you have help?

179
00:15:27,270 --> 00:15:29,990
One small Austrian lady
three times a week.

180
00:15:30,070 --> 00:15:32,670
And one large Austrian lady
four times a week.

181
00:15:32,750 --> 00:15:35,270
- What's for lunch?
- What would you like?

182
00:15:35,350 --> 00:15:37,310
You have any sausage?

183
00:15:37,350 --> 00:15:42,830
Oh, yeah. I have bratwurst,
liverwurst, weisswurst.

184
00:15:42,910 --> 00:15:45,550
How about some ham and eggs
and a beer?

185
00:15:45,590 --> 00:15:47,590
Kitchen's downstairs.

186
00:15:47,670 --> 00:15:49,750
Where do you keep
the beer, please?

187
00:15:49,830 --> 00:15:51,950
Middle shelf.

188
00:15:55,510 --> 00:15:59,550
- Miss the old life?
- No. Game got too dirty.

189
00:15:59,630 --> 00:16:02,230
You still take
gin and ginger ale?

190
00:16:02,310 --> 00:16:05,310
Mine was never
gin and ginger ale.

191
00:16:05,390 --> 00:16:07,550
Montrachet '69, please.
Next to the beer.

192
00:16:07,630 --> 00:16:10,670
Oh, of course.

193
00:16:12,830 --> 00:16:15,150
When I first worked
for the agency...

194
00:16:15,190 --> 00:16:17,390
its use seemed clear.

195
00:16:17,470 --> 00:16:20,310
You knew where you stood.
The bad guys wore mustaches.

196
00:16:20,390 --> 00:16:23,310
- Where's the opener?
- On the tray in front of you.

197
00:16:23,390 --> 00:16:25,310
Now...

198
00:16:25,390 --> 00:16:28,750
you need a scorecard to know
who the players are.

199
00:16:28,830 --> 00:16:30,750
Even then, it's fuzzy.

200
00:16:30,830 --> 00:16:34,110
- Where are the glasses?
- On the table in front of you.

201
00:16:34,190 --> 00:16:36,390
I'm glad I'm out.

202
00:16:36,470 --> 00:16:38,390
I'm out too.

203
00:16:38,470 --> 00:16:40,510
What?

204
00:16:40,590 --> 00:16:43,030
I quit, but they
don't know it yet.

205
00:16:43,110 --> 00:16:45,230
I can't imagine you
without the agency.

206
00:16:45,310 --> 00:16:47,230
It's your whole life.

207
00:16:47,310 --> 00:16:49,910
They put Myerson
in charge of my section.

208
00:16:49,990 --> 00:16:52,390
He wanted to retire me
behind a desk.

209
00:16:52,470 --> 00:16:56,950
"See you next Tuesday" Myerson
in charge? They've gone mad.

210
00:16:57,030 --> 00:16:59,430
He's got tapes on everybody
locked away.

211
00:16:59,470 --> 00:17:01,430
They're scared to death ofhim.

212
00:17:01,470 --> 00:17:04,470
- What are you going to do?
- I don't know. I'm working on it.

213
00:17:04,550 --> 00:17:06,470
Did you come to Salzburg
to see me?

214
00:17:06,550 --> 00:17:09,310
Mm! You and Mozart.

215
00:17:09,390 --> 00:17:11,550
Do they still keep
tabs on me in Washington?

216
00:17:11,630 --> 00:17:13,550
Well, we knew you married
some old Nazi.

217
00:17:13,630 --> 00:17:16,150
- Come on, Kendig. Hewas Austrian.
- So was Hitler.

218
00:17:16,230 --> 00:17:18,710
- Yes, but he had
no sense ofhumor.

219
00:17:18,750 --> 00:17:20,710
Do I pass inspection?

220
00:17:20,750 --> 00:17:22,750
Ah. You do.

221
00:17:22,830 --> 00:17:25,390
You're so sweet and delicious.

222
00:17:25,470 --> 00:17:28,790
- Mmm!
- What do you really want, hmm?

223
00:17:28,830 --> 00:17:30,910
Somewhere to hide while you
decide what you're going to do.

224
00:17:30,990 --> 00:17:33,830
Succor and solace
and a shoulder to cry on.

225
00:17:33,870 --> 00:17:37,230
- Sounds pretty good to me. - How'd
you like to play gin rummythis evening?

226
00:17:37,310 --> 00:17:40,430
- For how much?
- How much can you afford to lose?

227
00:18:01,150 --> 00:18:04,110
That's the second four
you've given me.

228
00:18:06,190 --> 00:18:09,630
Gin. Uh-huh, it's gin.

229
00:18:11,270 --> 00:18:13,830
- Hmm. Thirty-three.
- Aha!

230
00:18:13,870 --> 00:18:16,270
Blitzed and double blitzed.

231
00:18:16,350 --> 00:18:18,510
What do you do with yourself
around here anyway?

232
00:18:18,590 --> 00:18:20,550
Look after my late husband's
business interests.

233
00:18:20,630 --> 00:18:23,550
- I keep myself occupied.
- Wanna tell me about him?

234
00:18:23,630 --> 00:18:26,150
- No.
- Good.

235
00:18:26,230 --> 00:18:29,150
Four... nine.

236
00:18:35,790 --> 00:18:38,350
- You owe me...
- Shh, shh, shh.

237
00:18:45,270 --> 00:18:47,430
You still owe me...

238
00:18:47,510 --> 00:18:51,470
$135.62.

239
00:18:53,510 --> 00:18:55,430
Wanna take it out in trade?

240
00:18:55,510 --> 00:18:58,310
What do you have
that's worth that much?

241
00:19:00,430 --> 00:19:03,270
Like antiques?

242
00:19:07,750 --> 00:19:09,670
Come to bed.

243
00:19:09,750 --> 00:19:11,710
I thought you'd never ask.

244
00:20:39,550 --> 00:20:41,550
I hear you walked out
on your friends.

245
00:20:41,590 --> 00:20:43,830
You hear, or is this
a trial balloon?

246
00:20:43,910 --> 00:20:47,150
Did they force you out
because you did not arrest me?

247
00:20:47,230 --> 00:20:50,550
- Right.
- I feel a bit guilty about that.

248
00:20:50,630 --> 00:20:53,030
- I'd like to make amends.
- How?

249
00:20:53,110 --> 00:20:55,710
I'm offering to put you
right back into the game.

250
00:20:55,790 --> 00:20:59,670
Yaskov, Yaskov.
I'd make a useless double agent.

251
00:20:59,710 --> 00:21:01,670
Of course you would.

252
00:21:01,710 --> 00:21:04,910
Double agents must be
drab little people. Colorless.

253
00:21:04,990 --> 00:21:07,270
No, that would never
do for you.

254
00:21:07,310 --> 00:21:10,830
Listen, I want
to run you in the field...

255
00:21:10,910 --> 00:21:12,870
as my own agent.

256
00:21:16,030 --> 00:21:19,510
We'd make it worth
your while, of course.

257
00:21:19,590 --> 00:21:21,550
There is plenty of money.

258
00:21:29,390 --> 00:21:31,390
No.

259
00:21:33,390 --> 00:21:36,270
Money is too expensive
to be earned that way, Yaskov.

260
00:21:38,470 --> 00:21:42,230
Look. The human species
has been on this planet...

261
00:21:42,310 --> 00:21:45,990
for, um, millions of years.

262
00:21:46,070 --> 00:21:48,710
Except for the tiniest
fraction of the time...

263
00:21:48,790 --> 00:21:51,030
we all lived as hunters.

264
00:21:51,110 --> 00:21:55,390
Hunting... it's the only
natural way of life.

265
00:21:55,470 --> 00:21:59,190
It was your way of life
until you walked away from it.

266
00:21:59,270 --> 00:22:01,590
I'm offering to return it to you.

267
00:22:01,630 --> 00:22:05,270
- By the way, we are being photographed.
- Yours or mine?

268
00:22:06,830 --> 00:22:09,670
Yours.
I recognize the mustache.

269
00:22:09,710 --> 00:22:11,670
Oh, that's Follett.
He's an idiot.

270
00:22:11,710 --> 00:22:13,910
Probably no film
in the camera.

271
00:22:16,670 --> 00:22:18,590
Could you be
rejecting my offer...

272
00:22:18,670 --> 00:22:21,910
out of some absurd
loyalty to the flag?

273
00:22:21,950 --> 00:22:27,230
You may as well give up,
tovarich. Nyet interested.

274
00:22:27,310 --> 00:22:31,670
A pity. What do you intend to do
with the rest of your life, then?

275
00:22:31,750 --> 00:22:33,790
Write your memoirs?

276
00:22:35,630 --> 00:22:37,630
Memoirs?

277
00:22:37,710 --> 00:22:39,870
That's not a bad idea.

278
00:22:43,110 --> 00:22:45,870
- Have you got a typewriter?
- In the den.

279
00:22:45,950 --> 00:22:48,070
What are you going to do,
write some letters?

280
00:22:48,150 --> 00:22:51,030
- No. I'm going to write mymemoirs.
- Oh, that's nice.

281
00:22:51,110 --> 00:22:53,110
Your childhood in the ghetto?

282
00:22:53,190 --> 00:22:55,150
My last 30 years
in the ghetto.

283
00:22:55,190 --> 00:22:57,870
Uh-huh. You're going to relate
some amusing incidents.

284
00:22:57,950 --> 00:23:02,510
And some not so amusing.
Would you put on a record, please?

285
00:23:02,590 --> 00:23:05,470
- What are you going to write about?
- I'm going to tell the truth.

286
00:23:05,550 --> 00:23:07,830
Oh, it's a work of fiction.

287
00:23:07,910 --> 00:23:12,470
Ah. You didn't say that.
You didn't make that clear.

288
00:23:41,830 --> 00:23:43,990
Oh!

289
00:23:44,070 --> 00:23:47,230
What? What's the matter?

290
00:23:52,190 --> 00:23:56,110
You're insane. They will
obliterate you in five minutes.

291
00:23:56,190 --> 00:23:58,150
- It'll shake 'em up.
- Shake them up?

292
00:23:58,190 --> 00:24:00,150
They will send men
who will come and kill you.

293
00:24:00,230 --> 00:24:02,550
I'll keep one step
ahead of them. That's enough.

294
00:24:02,630 --> 00:24:05,030
Well, almost enough.
I need your help.

295
00:24:05,110 --> 00:24:07,430
Oh, no. No.
I'm very sorry. No.

296
00:24:07,510 --> 00:24:11,910
I have a nice life, a beautiful house,
money, the respect ofthe community.

297
00:24:11,990 --> 00:24:14,390
Don't look at me
like that. No!

298
00:24:18,550 --> 00:24:21,390
What do you
want me to do?

299
00:24:21,470 --> 00:24:26,430
Find me a copying machine, get me a
stack of 9x12 manila mailing envelopes.

300
00:24:26,510 --> 00:24:30,310
We are both mad.
Mad! Gone!

301
00:24:38,350 --> 00:24:41,350
I thought perhaps you could
shed some light on this.

302
00:24:41,390 --> 00:24:43,790
I know Kendig's a friend
of yours, Cutter, but...

303
00:24:43,830 --> 00:24:47,150
what the fuck is he doing
drinking vodka with Yaskov?

304
00:24:47,230 --> 00:24:49,190
Yaskov is the enemy, isn't he?

305
00:24:52,070 --> 00:24:55,030
I don't think this is
anything to worry about.

306
00:24:55,110 --> 00:24:57,230
They've known each other
for years.

307
00:24:57,310 --> 00:25:02,150
He and Yaskov used to exchange
people at Checkpoint Charlie.

308
00:25:02,230 --> 00:25:04,150
There's nothing sinister about it.

309
00:25:04,230 --> 00:25:08,510
In Munich, he turned him loose. And
now he's having a drink with him?

310
00:25:08,550 --> 00:25:10,950
Better have a look at this.

311
00:25:11,030 --> 00:25:13,030
"Kendig, M."

312
00:25:17,190 --> 00:25:19,150
Nothing sinister, huh?

313
00:25:19,230 --> 00:25:21,230
Why has he tampered
with his file?

314
00:25:23,470 --> 00:25:25,790
I don't think
this means a thing.

315
00:25:25,870 --> 00:25:28,510
Probably shouldn't have done it,
but it's typical of him.

316
00:25:28,590 --> 00:25:31,030
He doesn't want to be a number
in anybody's computer.

317
00:25:31,110 --> 00:25:33,750
Bullshit.
He's up to something.

318
00:25:33,830 --> 00:25:35,830
It's your job
to find out what it is.

319
00:26:02,270 --> 00:26:04,310
You like opera?

320
00:26:04,390 --> 00:26:07,230
- Yeah. You?
-Ja.

321
00:26:07,310 --> 00:26:09,870
- Was ist das?
- "Barber of Seville." Figaro.

322
00:26:09,950 --> 00:26:13,310
- Oh. By Mozart.
- No. That's the other Figaro.

323
00:26:13,350 --> 00:26:15,510
- Huh?
- That's the...

324
00:26:15,550 --> 00:26:17,870
- Figaro.
- Ah.

325
00:26:17,950 --> 00:26:19,910
- AufWiedersehen.
- AufWiedersehen.

326
00:26:41,950 --> 00:26:43,950
Paris.

327
00:26:45,430 --> 00:26:47,430
Peking.

328
00:26:49,630 --> 00:26:51,630
Moscow.

329
00:26:53,910 --> 00:26:55,910
Rome.

330
00:26:58,830 --> 00:27:00,830
London.

331
00:27:02,230 --> 00:27:05,310
Und Washington, D. C.

332
00:27:05,390 --> 00:27:07,870
He must be out
of his freaking mind.

333
00:27:07,910 --> 00:27:11,270
"Subjects to be covered in
future chapters will be...

334
00:27:11,350 --> 00:27:15,590
"How much did the department of dirty
tricks have to do with the plane crash...

335
00:27:15,670 --> 00:27:18,710
"which killed
Secretary Hammarskjold?

336
00:27:20,310 --> 00:27:24,270
C. I. A. future plans for
clandestine operations."

337
00:27:24,350 --> 00:27:30,150
My God! He sent copies to Moscow,
Peking, London, Paris, Bonn, and Rome.

338
00:27:30,230 --> 00:27:34,310
Do you know he can blow every
operation we've set up for two years.

339
00:27:34,390 --> 00:27:37,630
He can make some waves
ifhe goes through with it.

340
00:27:37,710 --> 00:27:39,790
I don't think it's funny, Joe.

341
00:27:39,870 --> 00:27:41,710
Of course it's funny, Leonard.

342
00:27:41,790 --> 00:27:45,070
He's out ofhis fucking mind.
Where is he?

343
00:27:45,150 --> 00:27:47,750
Well, that was mailed
from Salzburg.

344
00:27:47,830 --> 00:27:49,750
But Follett says that a guy
that looked like him...

345
00:27:49,830 --> 00:27:53,510
crossed over into Switzerland a couple of
days ago singing the "Barber of Seville."

346
00:27:53,550 --> 00:27:56,630
Sounds like Kendig
hoping we'll chase him.

347
00:27:56,710 --> 00:28:00,910
Well, let's tell Follett to quit playing
around and find the son of a bitch.

348
00:28:18,670 --> 00:28:21,030
Sit down.

349
00:28:41,430 --> 00:28:43,430
Voila.

350
00:28:43,510 --> 00:28:46,870
Three passports... blank.

351
00:28:46,950 --> 00:28:49,030
Three driving licenses... blank.

352
00:28:49,110 --> 00:28:51,110
And a credit card.

353
00:28:55,110 --> 00:28:57,070
"James Butler."

354
00:28:57,150 --> 00:29:00,710
There is no such a thing as a
blank credit card. You know that.

355
00:29:00,750 --> 00:29:04,670
These look okay. Everything except
the price you quoted on the telephone.

356
00:29:04,750 --> 00:29:07,670
Five thousand francs
for the passports.

357
00:29:07,750 --> 00:29:12,030
Two thousand for the licenses. And
forthe credit cards, five hundred.

358
00:29:12,110 --> 00:29:14,870
They are not hot.
The numbers have been changed.

359
00:29:14,950 --> 00:29:16,870
My department's on a budget.

360
00:29:16,950 --> 00:29:19,790
Mais, oui. So am I.

361
00:29:19,870 --> 00:29:23,190
How many years have I been
working for your agency, huh?

362
00:29:23,270 --> 00:29:25,190
Am I not always reliable?

363
00:29:25,270 --> 00:29:28,470
Don't I deserve
any consideration?

364
00:29:28,510 --> 00:29:31,510
Six thousand for the package.
That's it.

365
00:29:31,590 --> 00:29:34,710
Impossible.

366
00:29:34,790 --> 00:29:37,550
Impossible.

367
00:29:37,590 --> 00:29:40,390
Tell you what.
I'll give you 7,000.

368
00:29:40,470 --> 00:29:42,390
Leave me with 500, will ya?

369
00:29:42,470 --> 00:29:46,190
- For what?
- For what?

370
00:29:46,230 --> 00:29:48,550
Cherchezla femme.

371
00:29:48,630 --> 00:29:51,070
Uh... a sandwich or something?

372
00:29:51,150 --> 00:29:53,750
I don't think he'll publish it.

373
00:29:53,830 --> 00:29:56,630
He's sending copies to the
intelligence people, not the publishers.

374
00:29:56,670 --> 00:29:59,150
It's his fucking suicide note.
The bastard wants...

375
00:29:59,230 --> 00:30:02,590
to go down in flames, and he wants
us to put him out of his misery.

376
00:30:02,670 --> 00:30:04,590
He's not the suicidal type.

377
00:30:04,670 --> 00:30:07,430
You put him on the bench. He's
putting himself back in the game.

378
00:30:07,510 --> 00:30:10,870
- That's what it's all about.
- The game is over.

379
00:30:12,950 --> 00:30:15,790
Listen, this is just a teaser.
This is just one chapter.

380
00:30:15,870 --> 00:30:17,870
Suppose we don't take the bait.

381
00:30:17,950 --> 00:30:20,950
If we don't play,
he'll probably have to quit.

382
00:30:21,030 --> 00:30:23,550
It's no fun playing byyourself.

383
00:30:23,630 --> 00:30:25,990
I've got a meeting
of the Security Council.

384
00:30:26,070 --> 00:30:28,270
Walk me out.

385
00:30:28,350 --> 00:30:30,270
I don't think you understand.

386
00:30:30,350 --> 00:30:32,310
On this play,
we have got to take him out.

387
00:30:32,390 --> 00:30:34,910
Because if we don't,
they will.

388
00:30:34,990 --> 00:30:36,990
The Soviets will read that teaser...

389
00:30:37,070 --> 00:30:40,150
and realize how much information
he's got in his pointed little head.

390
00:30:40,230 --> 00:30:42,710
They'll drop everything in a rush
to grab him alive and squeeze him.

391
00:30:42,790 --> 00:30:45,310
We can't afford that, can we?

392
00:30:45,390 --> 00:30:47,630
I want you on this full-time
as of right now.

393
00:30:47,710 --> 00:30:50,630
Anything you need, you ask for.
Top priority.

394
00:30:50,710 --> 00:30:52,630
I want you to cancel his ticket.

395
00:30:52,710 --> 00:30:55,310
We don't have to do that.
Let me try and stop him.

396
00:30:55,390 --> 00:30:57,390
You're on overtime, Cutter.

397
00:30:58,590 --> 00:31:00,590
Chemin de fer.

398
00:31:00,670 --> 00:31:03,070
The bank closes this time
six to seven.

399
00:31:03,150 --> 00:31:05,230
And the shoe passes
to a new bank.

400
00:31:07,430 --> 00:31:10,150
Thank you.
Place your bets. Thank you.

401
00:31:10,230 --> 00:31:12,270
- Thank you very much.
- Thank you, sir.

402
00:31:12,350 --> 00:31:14,670
- Sir, good night.
- Goodnight.

403
00:31:14,750 --> 00:31:16,750
Would you like smoking
or nonsmoking?

404
00:31:16,830 --> 00:31:21,190
Oh, nonsmoking, please, but make it an
aisle seat. I go to the bathroom a lot.

405
00:31:21,230 --> 00:31:23,230
Okay. Fine.

406
00:31:24,350 --> 00:31:26,270
Have you traveled Concorde before?

407
00:31:26,350 --> 00:31:28,590
No, not to the best
of my recollection.

408
00:31:28,630 --> 00:31:30,950
I understand you get there
before you leave.

409
00:31:31,030 --> 00:31:32,950
Yes, that's right.
There you are, sir.

410
00:31:33,030 --> 00:31:35,510
- Thank you very much. Have a
pleasant flight. - Thank you.

411
00:31:43,550 --> 00:31:46,950
Okay. We know he's traveling
under the name of James Butler.

412
00:31:47,030 --> 00:31:49,030
For the time being.

413
00:31:49,110 --> 00:31:51,110
We know he left
the Grand Hotel in Marseilles...

414
00:31:51,190 --> 00:31:53,430
tookan Air France
to Heathrow.

415
00:31:53,510 --> 00:31:56,990
We know hewon f10,000
at the Grovener Casino...

416
00:31:57,070 --> 00:31:59,270
and we're assuming
that he's still in London.

417
00:31:59,350 --> 00:32:02,310
- You got a nail file? - I'd like to
have a look at his travel vouchers...

418
00:32:02,390 --> 00:32:04,310
for the last year or two.

419
00:32:04,390 --> 00:32:06,590
Might be something in there,
some pattern of movement.

420
00:32:06,670 --> 00:32:09,070
You won't find anything
consistent on him.

421
00:32:09,150 --> 00:32:12,910
His checks keep bouncing
'cause his signature varies.

422
00:32:12,990 --> 00:32:14,910
He's a class act.

423
00:32:14,990 --> 00:32:17,630
You like the guy, don't you?

424
00:32:17,710 --> 00:32:20,030
Yes, I like him.

425
00:32:22,910 --> 00:32:24,910
Let's get something to eat.

426
00:32:30,470 --> 00:32:32,470
I'll get it.

427
00:32:36,510 --> 00:32:37,990
762.

428
00:32:38,070 --> 00:32:40,390
No. This is Leonard Ross.
Who's calling?

429
00:32:48,870 --> 00:32:50,870
Start a trace.

430
00:32:53,230 --> 00:32:55,150
Kendig,
what a pleasant surprise.

431
00:32:55,230 --> 00:32:59,390
-Joe Cutter. Well, I'm glad they put
in the first team. - Thank you.

432
00:32:59,470 --> 00:33:02,230
I mailed out another
chapter this morning.

433
00:33:02,310 --> 00:33:05,430
If you're collecting stamps,
it's postmarked London.

434
00:33:05,510 --> 00:33:07,430
What are you trying to prove?

435
00:33:07,510 --> 00:33:11,750
I'm not trying to prove anything,
Joe. I'm just trying to have some fun.

436
00:33:11,830 --> 00:33:13,790
Suppose you let me
talk you out of this...

437
00:33:13,870 --> 00:33:17,710
before you find yourself at the
bottom of some river sipping sewage.

438
00:33:17,790 --> 00:33:20,710
I'll be mailing it out
one chapter at a time.

439
00:33:20,750 --> 00:33:22,710
Be more interesting that way.

440
00:33:22,750 --> 00:33:25,910
You can tell Myerson that I'm
saving the juicy stuff for the end.

441
00:33:25,950 --> 00:33:29,830
Listen, Kendig, I'm the one who's
gonna have to do the dirty work.

442
00:33:29,910 --> 00:33:31,990
I don't want that.

443
00:33:32,070 --> 00:33:35,270
Think of me, can't you? Don't you
have any feelings for me at all?

444
00:33:35,350 --> 00:33:37,590
I'm gonna be tortured by this
for the rest ofmy life.

445
00:33:37,670 --> 00:33:39,870
All my money will go
to a psychiatrist.

446
00:33:39,950 --> 00:33:43,430
That's very good, Joe. Very dramatic.
I've never heard that used before.

447
00:33:43,510 --> 00:33:48,150
Well, I think you've had time
to locate this call by now, kid.

448
00:33:48,230 --> 00:33:51,150
So I'll be saying so long.
I'll see you around some time.

449
00:33:51,230 --> 00:33:53,710
Kendig.
Kendig, are you there?

450
00:33:59,190 --> 00:34:01,150
Did you get a line on that?

451
00:34:01,190 --> 00:34:03,230
Are you sure?

452
00:34:03,310 --> 00:34:05,510
That son of a bitch.

453
00:34:05,590 --> 00:34:08,030
He's right here in Washington.
It's a local call.

454
00:34:21,430 --> 00:34:23,030
- Anything?
- Nothing.

455
00:34:23,070 --> 00:34:26,190
- He's probably halfway to the moon by now.
- Don't sound so pleased.

456
00:34:29,390 --> 00:34:31,870
I've got everyone who knows him
by sight working the streets.

457
00:34:31,950 --> 00:34:34,590
- Good work, Leonard.
- What would you suggest...

458
00:34:34,670 --> 00:34:37,070
we just go back and wait
for the phone to ring again?

459
00:34:37,150 --> 00:34:39,550
I don't think he's gonna call
again. He said what he has to say.

460
00:34:39,590 --> 00:34:41,550
Excuse me, sir.

461
00:34:41,590 --> 00:34:43,590
We found this under "B"
in the phone book.

462
00:34:47,870 --> 00:34:51,510
I think we can say
good-bye to James Butler.

463
00:35:02,710 --> 00:35:04,750
- Is everything okay?
-Yeah, thanks.

464
00:35:04,830 --> 00:35:07,110
- More coffee?
- No, thank you.

465
00:35:16,230 --> 00:35:18,230
Hello, Operator.

466
00:35:18,270 --> 00:35:21,990
I'd like to make a "bill to" call
to overseas, please.

467
00:35:37,150 --> 00:35:39,110
- Hello?
- Hi, Is.

468
00:35:39,150 --> 00:35:42,230
Right on time. How are you?
Did you have a safe trip?

469
00:35:42,310 --> 00:35:44,590
Yes. I said hello
to the folks.

470
00:35:44,670 --> 00:35:47,230
They were surprised
to hear from me.

471
00:35:47,310 --> 00:35:49,230
Have any of them
paid you a visit?

472
00:35:49,310 --> 00:35:53,750
Only friend Follett.
He's watching me right now.

473
00:35:53,830 --> 00:35:57,070
Give him a kiss for me
and tell him I'll write.

474
00:35:57,150 --> 00:35:59,950
I'm sure he'd be very interested
to hear from you.

475
00:36:00,030 --> 00:36:02,030
Now, you remember...

476
00:36:02,110 --> 00:36:04,070
when and where
I'm gonna call you next.

477
00:36:04,110 --> 00:36:07,710
Of course I remember.
And you remember to be careful.

478
00:36:07,790 --> 00:36:09,710
And if you should happen
to see Kendig...

479
00:36:09,790 --> 00:36:12,670
tell the horny old goat
I miss him very much and love him.

480
00:36:12,750 --> 00:36:17,390
- Good-bye, Mr... - Hannaway.
Charlie Hannaway.

481
00:36:17,470 --> 00:36:19,830
