717
00:54:51,510 --> 00:54:53,990
What secrets did he steal?

718
00:54:54,070 --> 00:54:56,870
It's on a need-to-know basis...
a matter of national security.

719
00:54:56,950 --> 00:54:59,430
Yeah.

720
00:54:59,510 --> 00:55:02,150
That's a phrase that's lost
a good deal of meaning lately.

721
00:55:06,910 --> 00:55:08,870
You got 20 seconds, Kendig.

722
00:55:25,470 --> 00:55:27,470
Give him the gas.

723
00:55:38,110 --> 00:55:41,590
Do that one more time, Kendig,
and we'll blow you to pieces.

724
00:55:43,870 --> 00:55:45,510
Let him have it.

725
00:55:57,230 --> 00:56:00,790
Freeze!
Keep your hands down.

726
00:56:00,870 --> 00:56:05,390
Nice shootin', Ross. Eight thousand
panes, and you hit one of them.

727
00:56:07,470 --> 00:56:10,830
- What's happening?
- They're shooting up your house.

728
00:56:18,790 --> 00:56:21,350
Stop it! Stop it!

729
00:56:21,390 --> 00:56:23,350
Cease fire!

730
00:56:23,390 --> 00:56:26,870
Fucking Idiots!

731
00:56:26,950 --> 00:56:29,270
Stop it! Stop it!

732
00:56:29,350 --> 00:56:32,070
Get down, you idiot!
You wanna get yourself killed?

733
00:56:33,510 --> 00:56:35,470
This is a mistake!

734
00:56:35,550 --> 00:56:37,470
- In you go, Ross.
- Am I driving?

735
00:56:37,550 --> 00:56:39,590
Move over to the other side.
Move it.

736
00:56:42,230 --> 00:56:44,150
That's enough!
That's enough!

737
00:56:44,230 --> 00:56:47,190
- You're destroying my house!
- Give it one more.

738
00:56:49,230 --> 00:56:51,230
Okay, boys. Cease fire.

739
00:56:52,630 --> 00:56:55,630
Soon as the smoke clears,
we'll go in and take a look.

740
00:56:58,630 --> 00:57:01,110
I don't believe this.

741
00:57:01,190 --> 00:57:03,190
I don't fucking believe this.

742
00:57:03,270 --> 00:57:05,630
- Talk about playing into this hands.
-Just shut the fuck up!

743
00:57:05,670 --> 00:57:07,630
There's a guy pulling
out of here in a pickup...

744
00:57:07,670 --> 00:57:09,630
with one ofthe C. I. A. men.

745
00:57:09,670 --> 00:57:11,670
Ross!

746
00:57:17,950 --> 00:57:20,990
- That's him!
- Back to the cars.

747
00:57:23,670 --> 00:57:26,350
- I'll call the fire department.
- Son of a bitch!

748
00:57:29,470 --> 00:57:31,390
Mike, stay here.

749
00:57:31,470 --> 00:57:33,950
Let's go!

750
00:58:15,710 --> 00:58:18,630
Now I know what
F. B. I. stands for.

751
00:58:18,710 --> 00:58:21,110
Fucking Ball-busting
Imbeciles.

752
00:58:26,190 --> 00:58:29,150
Okay, Ross.
This is where you get off.

753
00:58:29,230 --> 00:58:31,990
You used to be a pretty
good man. I looked up to you.

754
00:58:32,070 --> 00:58:34,150
- What happened?
- Get out.

755
00:58:34,230 --> 00:58:37,870
- I came to my senses, that's all.
- How do you figure that?

756
00:58:37,950 --> 00:58:41,150
A few skunks in the agency
that needed flushing out.

757
00:58:41,230 --> 00:58:43,190
Close the door.
Back off.

758
00:58:46,110 --> 00:58:49,390
You're just making a fool of yourself,
Kendig. You don't have a chance.

759
00:58:49,470 --> 00:58:51,630
Oh, yeah?

760
00:58:51,670 --> 00:58:54,870
Don't bet on that, Ross.
So long, kid.

761
00:59:43,990 --> 00:59:46,670
- Mornin'.
- Good mornin'.

762
01:00:01,950 --> 01:00:04,870
- Hiya, kid.
- Hi.

763
01:00:05,870 --> 01:00:07,790
- You alone?
- Yeah.

764
01:00:07,870 --> 01:00:10,950
- Where's your lady friend?
- Her mother wouldn't let her come.

765
01:00:11,030 --> 01:00:13,030
Okay. Let's get going.

766
01:00:21,150 --> 01:00:24,270
One passenger or two...
the price is still the same.

767
01:00:24,350 --> 01:00:27,030
Oh, that's a relief.

768
01:00:27,070 --> 01:00:29,990
Three thousand bucks.
There we go.

769
01:00:30,070 --> 01:00:32,590
Thank you.
Next stop... Martinique.

770
01:00:32,670 --> 01:00:34,590
How about a change of course?

771
01:00:34,670 --> 01:00:37,110
092 magnetic.

772
01:00:37,190 --> 01:00:39,190
- Bermuda?
- Why not?

773
01:00:39,270 --> 01:00:42,150
Okay by me. That'll take
about seven hours.

774
01:00:42,230 --> 01:00:44,550
We haven't got a bathroom.
Can you make it?

775
01:00:44,630 --> 01:00:47,990
- I'll be very careful.
- What did you do, rob a bank?

776
01:00:48,070 --> 01:00:50,630
- Is that what's in the suitcase?
- Uh, yes.

777
01:00:50,710 --> 01:00:55,230
Gee, I never drove a get away
car before. It's kind offun.

778
01:00:55,310 --> 01:00:58,470
- You mind ifl steer a while?
- You know how?

779
01:00:58,550 --> 01:01:01,710
Yeah. They trained me as
a ferry pilot for M. A. T. S.

780
01:01:01,790 --> 01:01:05,470
- Still got my license.
- Sure. Who's "they"?

781
01:01:05,550 --> 01:01:08,110
Guys with little
plastic I. D. cards.

782
01:01:08,190 --> 01:01:10,510
They'll probably come around,
ask you a lot of questions.

783
01:01:10,550 --> 01:01:12,510
Just tell them the truth.

784
01:01:12,550 --> 01:01:14,870
I generally tell the truth.
It's easier that way.

785
01:01:27,870 --> 01:01:29,830
- Are you going back tonight?
- Oh, noway.

786
01:01:29,870 --> 01:01:32,270
I'm gonna get my hair done
and get a good night's sleep.

787
01:01:32,350 --> 01:01:35,630
- Well, you certainly got enough
money for it. -Just about.

788
01:01:35,670 --> 01:01:38,070
So long. Take care of yourself,
whatever you're doing.

789
01:01:38,110 --> 01:01:41,190
You seem like a nice fella.
You remind me of my father.

790
01:01:41,270 --> 01:01:43,670
That's always been my problem.

791
01:02:25,750 --> 01:02:28,910
Here's your tea, dear. Nice and hot,
with lemon. Just the way you like it.

792
01:02:28,990 --> 01:02:30,910
I don't like lemon.
I like milk.

793
01:02:30,990 --> 01:02:34,190
Now, is there anything else
that I can get for you boys?

794
01:02:34,230 --> 01:02:37,230
Well, don't work Mr. Cutter too
hard. After all, it is Sunday.

795
01:02:37,270 --> 01:02:41,110
I'm sure he needs his rest. If you
need me, I'll be in the sewing room.

796
01:02:41,190 --> 01:02:44,470
Should have terminated her
20 years ago.

797
01:02:44,510 --> 01:02:49,910
Joe, maybewe've been going
about this the wrong way.

798
01:02:49,950 --> 01:02:51,950
Perhaps it needs
a lighter touch.

799
01:02:52,030 --> 01:02:55,510
You know, sometimes bullying
people doesn'twork.

800
01:02:55,590 --> 01:02:57,950
Let's be sophisticated here.

801
01:02:57,990 --> 01:03:01,870
Maybe we can use a carrot
instead of a stick.

802
01:03:02,990 --> 01:03:05,110
Kendig likes girls,
doesn't he?

803
01:03:05,190 --> 01:03:07,230
Listen, Myerson,
let me make a suggestion.

804
01:03:07,310 --> 01:03:10,750
Why don't I go over to Salzburg
and have a little talk with Isobel?

805
01:03:10,830 --> 01:03:13,910
We worked together once. Maybe
she'll listen to what I have to say.

806
01:03:15,190 --> 01:03:19,150
Have you got something
going on with Isobel too?

807
01:03:19,230 --> 01:03:22,310
We're always
one step behind him.

808
01:03:22,390 --> 01:03:25,630
I'd like to get one step ahead
ofthe arrogant son ofa bitch.

809
01:03:25,710 --> 01:03:29,110
I thought you liked
the arrogant son of a bitch?

810
01:03:29,150 --> 01:03:33,110
-Welcome to London, Mr. Ross.
Business or pleasure? - Oh, yes.

811
01:03:33,190 --> 01:03:35,830
- I beg your pardon?
- Oh. A little ofboth.

812
01:03:35,910 --> 01:03:39,790
- I'm here to see my publisher. I'm writing
a book. - How long do you plan to stay?

813
01:03:39,830 --> 01:03:43,750
That depends. I'm waiting for
some colleagues to catch upwith me.

814
01:03:43,830 --> 01:03:45,750
- Enjoy your visit.
- Thank you.

815
01:03:45,830 --> 01:03:47,750
- What's the name of the book?
- Hopscotch.

816
01:03:47,830 --> 01:03:49,830
Good title.

817
01:04:03,550 --> 01:04:05,470
- Glen.
- How are you doing?

818
01:04:05,550 --> 01:04:09,150
- Will she see us? - She'll see you. You
won't get anywhere. I've already tried.

819
01:04:09,190 --> 01:04:12,390
Well, maybe she'll be more
accessible to me. I'm an old friend.

820
01:04:12,470 --> 01:04:16,670
- Yaskov's in town. He wants to see you.
- That's good. I'd like that.

821
01:04:16,750 --> 01:04:18,990
Set a time and place
for this afternoon.

822
01:04:19,070 --> 01:04:22,230
You're looking very tired, Joe.

823
01:04:22,310 --> 01:04:26,550
- It's the jet lag. I can't get used to it.
- You sure that's all it is?

824
01:04:26,630 --> 01:04:30,510
Now, listen, Isobel. We're
both fond ofthis character...

825
01:04:30,590 --> 01:04:34,150
but he's making an ass of himself,
and he's got to cut it out.

826
01:04:34,230 --> 01:04:37,710
- For his own good.
- For his own good?

827
01:04:37,790 --> 01:04:41,030
You've been trying to stop him, and
I gather not having too much success.

828
01:04:41,110 --> 01:04:43,710
Such a shame.
All those bright young men.

829
01:04:43,790 --> 01:04:47,830
And there he is, single-handedly
running rings around you all.

830
01:04:47,910 --> 01:04:50,310
He's very good.
He's as good as they come.

831
01:04:50,390 --> 01:04:53,830
And he is running rings around us,
and I'm his biggest fan.

832
01:04:54,910 --> 01:04:57,030
But Kendig is going
to make a mistake.

833
01:04:57,070 --> 01:05:00,670
Sooner orlater, he's bound to slip.
Afterall, he's only human.

834
01:05:00,750 --> 01:05:05,030
- Oh, he's extremely human.
- It's not funny, Isobel.

835
01:05:05,110 --> 01:05:09,550
We're not the only people looking for him.
If the Russians get to him before we do...

836
01:05:09,590 --> 01:05:14,070
You mean Myerson's methods of termination
are more humane than the Russians'?

837
01:05:14,150 --> 01:05:16,990
You know what I mean.

838
01:05:17,070 --> 01:05:21,590
I don't want to hurt him, Isobel. But I
have a job to do, and I'm going to do it.

839
01:05:21,670 --> 01:05:23,950
He's got to stop
that book right now.

840
01:05:24,030 --> 01:05:28,510
He's hadhis fun. He's made a fool
out of everyone. Now he has to stop.

841
01:05:28,590 --> 01:05:31,430
He has to stop
ifhe's going to stay alive.

842
01:05:32,710 --> 01:05:36,310
- Will you tell him?
- Oh, I'll tell him.

843
01:05:36,390 --> 01:05:38,470
I don't think he'll stop.

844
01:05:38,550 --> 01:05:40,910
Oh. You've forgotten your beer.

845
01:05:51,110 --> 01:05:54,950
- Hi. I'm looking for Mr. Ludlow.
- Ah, you mean Mr. Ludlum.

846
01:05:55,030 --> 01:05:57,790
- You'll find him in his office
up there, gov. - Thank you.

847
01:06:06,870 --> 01:06:09,030
- Mr. Ludlum?
- Yes, sir.

848
01:06:09,110 --> 01:06:11,830
I understand you have
a little old airplane for sale.

849
01:06:11,910 --> 01:06:14,670
- I'm Ross. I called you this morning.
- Ah, yes, sir. Yes.

850
01:06:14,750 --> 01:06:17,710
- You'd like to take a little look,
would you? - Yeah, please.

851
01:06:18,830 --> 01:06:21,270
She's a Stampe, sir.

852
01:06:21,350 --> 01:06:24,350
Oh, the Belgian version
ofthe old Tiger Moth.

853
01:06:24,390 --> 01:06:27,230
- Yes, indeed. You know your aircraft, sir.
- Mm.

854
01:06:27,310 --> 01:06:30,390
She trained a lot of good
fighter pilots in her day.

855
01:06:30,470 --> 01:06:33,990
- How many hours on the engine? - A hundred
and eighteen since the last overhaul.

856
01:06:34,070 --> 01:06:37,390
- A hundred and eighty? -
Eighteen, sir. One-eight.

857
01:06:37,470 --> 01:06:41,270
- She's generally in very good shape.
- How much are you asking?

858
01:06:41,350 --> 01:06:44,430
Well, you'll need to have a look at
the logs and certifications, won't you?

859
01:06:44,510 --> 01:06:48,430
- So let's nip back to the office and
see what we can do. - Okay.

860
01:06:55,390 --> 01:06:59,710
Look at Yaskov. He must have
seen Casablanca 12 times.

861
01:07:04,550 --> 01:07:06,550
You better wait here.

862
01:07:13,430 --> 01:07:16,430
- I know where he is.
- Who's that, comrade?

863
01:07:17,630 --> 01:07:20,870
May I suggest we pool
our information?

864
01:07:20,950 --> 01:07:25,510
If I tell you the city, you will know
how to find him in that city, yes?

865
01:07:25,550 --> 01:07:31,070
- A new wrinkle on detente. - That
manuscript is an embarrassment to us all.

866
01:07:31,150 --> 01:07:35,070
If you catch him, your people will squeeze
him. We're not crazy about that idea.

867
01:07:35,150 --> 01:07:38,070
At the moment, we feel it is more
important he be neutralized.

868
01:07:38,150 --> 01:07:42,310
He knows too much about
our side, as well as yours.

869
01:07:42,390 --> 01:07:44,790
Well?

870
01:07:44,870 --> 01:07:46,790
Sorry.

871
01:07:46,870 --> 01:07:49,430
Very well.
He is back in London.

872
01:07:51,790 --> 01:07:54,110
He flew there from Bermuda
two days ago.

873
01:07:54,190 --> 01:07:59,350
- He's traveling under the name
of Leonard Ross. - That figures.

874
01:07:59,430 --> 01:08:02,710
I'd like to be able to tell you that we
found him through brilliant detective work.

875
01:08:02,790 --> 01:08:08,550
But in actual fact, one of my men just
happened to recognize him at Heathrow.

876
01:08:08,630 --> 01:08:12,270
I will want a quid pro quo
one day, my good friend.

877
01:08:12,350 --> 01:08:14,470
I bet you will.

878
01:08:14,550 --> 01:08:16,550
See you in London.

879
01:08:19,710 --> 01:08:21,670
- Well?
- He's in London.

880
01:08:21,710 --> 01:08:25,710
- He gave you that for free? - Of course
not. Nothing's free with that old fox.

881
01:08:25,790 --> 01:08:28,350
But it does tell us one thing.

882
01:08:28,430 --> 01:08:31,430
- The Russians are just as nervous
as we are. - You're learning.

883
01:08:31,510 --> 01:08:34,630
By the way, he's traveling
on your passport.

884
01:08:46,070 --> 01:08:49,150
That's cheaper too.

885
01:08:55,710 --> 01:08:58,550
Uh, no, I'm sorry. Sorry.

886
01:08:58,630 --> 01:09:02,390
- Parlez-vous Francais, monsieur?
- No, no. This...

887
01:09:02,470 --> 01:09:04,710
Can you speak French
or German, either of you?

888
01:09:04,750 --> 01:09:07,310
Does Alfie Booker
still work here?

889
01:09:08,990 --> 01:09:12,550
- Yeah. He's out in the back.
- May I speak to him for a moment, please?

890
01:09:12,630 --> 01:09:15,150
- Sure. Help yourself.
- Thank you.

891
01:09:17,190 --> 01:09:20,470
- Here, I'll take this one myself.
- Yeah, I like that one.

892
01:09:25,670 --> 01:09:28,470
Alfred P. Booker.

893
01:09:28,550 --> 01:09:32,070
Mr. Kendig. Hey, it's good to see you.
It's been two years.

894
01:09:32,110 --> 01:09:34,070
- You lost a little weight, didn't you?
- Yeah.

895
01:09:34,150 --> 01:09:37,950
- Hey, how'd that transistor job
go for you? - The transistor?

896
01:09:37,990 --> 01:09:42,470
What... Oh, they never even
knew it was there. Not a clue.

897
01:09:42,550 --> 01:09:44,990
I have something a little more
difficult for you this time.

898
01:09:45,070 --> 01:09:47,230
May I come
around here, please?

899
01:09:51,710 --> 01:09:54,190
Tell me how practical
you think that is.

900
01:10:01,110 --> 01:10:04,150
- Where are we staying?
- The Hilton. - Good.

901
01:10:04,230 --> 01:10:07,110
And I set up a meeting for this
afternoon with British Intelligence.

902
01:10:07,190 --> 01:10:09,550
Yeah, well, there's no problem
with the electronic stuff.

903
01:10:09,630 --> 01:10:13,230
That's dead easy. But it's the
mechanics I'm not sure about.

904
01:10:13,310 --> 01:10:17,950
Servo motors, some sort
of hydraulic transfer.

905
01:10:17,990 --> 01:10:21,190
Look, there is a chap I know in the
navy, used to know all about this stuff.

906
01:10:21,270 --> 01:10:24,390
Do you want me to get ahold of
him and see ifhe can help us?

907
01:10:24,470 --> 01:10:27,470
- How low do you think it will take?
- Give me a ring tonight.

908
01:10:27,510 --> 01:10:29,750
I'll know by then if I can get
a hold of him. And if I can...

909
01:10:29,830 --> 01:10:33,190
I'll go down to the field
tomorrow morning.

910
01:10:33,270 --> 01:10:35,710
Could have it installed for you
by nightfall. How's that sound?

911
01:10:35,790 --> 01:10:40,230
All right, I'll call you. Just give me
your home phone number, if you please.

912
01:10:40,310 --> 01:10:42,270
Yeah.

913
01:10:45,350 --> 01:10:49,470
You understand, Sir Giles, this requires
a certain delicacy on all our parts.

914
01:10:49,550 --> 01:10:52,710
Yes, I'm sure it must be terribly
embarrassing for all of you.

915
01:10:52,790 --> 01:10:54,761
Of course, we in
England would never allow

916
01:10:54,762 --> 01:10:57,190
ourselves to get into such
a ridiculous predicament.

917
01:10:57,230 --> 01:11:00,030
- You see, what we need is...
- Yes, yes, yes, I know.

918
01:11:00,070 --> 01:11:02,390
But it's quite fascinating,
isn't it? The part where...

919
01:11:02,470 --> 01:11:05,670
I think it's chapter three...
the bit about Somoza, Nicaragua.

920
01:11:05,710 --> 01:11:08,390
Your Kendig's got
quite a sense of humor.

921
01:11:08,470 --> 01:11:11,590
Sir Giles, we would appreciate it
if we could move forward with this.

922
01:11:11,670 --> 01:11:15,230
Technically, it's not our problem,
is it? He's broken no laws in Britain.

923
01:11:15,310 --> 01:11:19,310
But, of course, hands across the sea and
all that. We'll be happy to cooperate.

924
01:11:19,390 --> 01:11:22,910
- Now, what exactly would you like
to have us do? -Manpower.

925
01:11:22,990 --> 01:11:25,190
We'd like you to put a lot
of people on the ports of exit...

926
01:11:25,270 --> 01:11:27,270
airlines, terminals, that stuff.

927
01:11:27,350 --> 01:11:30,680
Well, that does seem
to be rather fruitless.

928
01:11:30,730 --> 01:11:32,470
We don't really know what he looks like.

929
01:11:32,550 --> 01:11:35,190
We do have this, sir.

930
01:11:35,270 --> 01:11:38,390
Ah. Thank you.
Which one is, uh...

931
01:11:38,470 --> 01:11:41,710
Well, that's Yaskov.
What's he doing with Yaskov?

932
01:11:41,790 --> 01:11:44,910
- That's part of our problem.
- The main thing is...

933
01:11:44,990 --> 01:11:46,910
I'll have a word with the police.

934
01:11:46,990 --> 01:11:49,830
- We'll circulate copies of this to all
ports of exit. - The main thing is...

935
01:11:49,910 --> 01:11:53,350
he's come to England for a reason;
he didn't pick it out of a hat.

936
01:11:53,390 --> 01:11:55,790
We think he's here to
find a publisher.

937
01:11:55,850 --> 01:11:57,590
There can only be so many
publishers in London.

938
01:11:57,670 --> 01:12:01,790
A dozen or so major houses.
Perhaps 30 or 40 small presses.

939
01:12:01,870 --> 01:12:04,590
He wants to make a big noise,
so he'd go to a big house.

940
01:12:04,630 --> 01:12:07,030
But I think that's what
he'll think we're thinking...

941
01:12:07,070 --> 01:12:08,950
so I think he'll
go to a small one.

942
01:12:09,030 --> 01:12:12,790
All right. I've got friends
in some of the publishing firms.

943
01:12:12,870 --> 01:12:15,230
I'll get in touch
and let you know what I learn.

944
01:12:15,310 --> 01:12:17,670
- Where are you staying?
- The Hilton.

945
01:12:17,710 --> 01:12:22,270
Yes, of course. I'll ring the Hilton the
instant we've got anything of interest.

946
01:12:23,550 --> 01:12:25,670
Good-bye, Mr. Myerson.

947
01:12:27,270 --> 01:12:31,350
- Yes, can I help you? - Can you call
Salzburg, Austria, for me, please?

948
01:12:33,230 --> 01:12:36,190
Yes, of course.
If you'd like to sit down...

949
01:12:36,230 --> 01:12:38,910
- I'll tell you as soon as we get through.
- Thank you.

950
01:13:15,230 --> 01:13:18,790
-The feathers in what?
- The Feathers Inn.

951
01:13:18,870 --> 01:13:21,310
The Feathers Inn.
Sorry, sorry, sorry.

952
01:13:21,350 --> 01:13:25,150
- Don't you remember, darling?
-Of course I remember, darling.

953
01:13:32,790 --> 01:13:35,950
Why don't you go get
some lunch. I'll take over.

954
01:13:35,990 --> 01:13:37,990
All right. Thanks.

955
01:13:52,990 --> 01:13:55,990
Ah, Mr. Follett. Come in.

956
01:13:58,870 --> 01:14:00,870
Thankyou.

957
01:14:11,590 --> 01:14:14,390
- What'd you want to see me about?
- Won't you sit down?

958
01:14:17,350 --> 01:14:21,630
I wanted to see you: A... Because I'm
tired of being watched 24 hours a day...

959
01:14:21,710 --> 01:14:24,470
and feel that you and I could come
to some more civilized arraignment.

960
01:14:24,550 --> 01:14:29,190
And B... I have just been speaking
on the telephone with Kendig.

961
01:14:29,270 --> 01:14:31,470
- Where was he calling from?
- He didn't say.

962
01:14:31,550 --> 01:14:35,390
He did say, however, he feels that this
has now become a ridiculous charade...

963
01:14:35,470 --> 01:14:37,430
that we should all stop playing.

964
01:14:37,510 --> 01:14:39,990
We'd be delighted
to stop playing.

965
01:14:40,070 --> 01:14:42,630
- Would you like a drink?
- Thank you.

966
01:14:42,710 --> 01:14:44,630
A little whiskey maybe.

967
01:14:44,710 --> 01:14:49,270
Good. Kendig would
like to speak to you...

968
01:14:49,350 --> 01:14:52,750
because he's too emotionally
involved with the others.

969
01:14:52,830 --> 01:14:55,270
He said he would telephone
about 1:30, which is...

970
01:14:55,350 --> 01:14:59,950
Oh, in 15 minutes. I said I felt sure
you would be here to take the call.

971
01:15:00,030 --> 01:15:03,470
No ice. Excuse me.

972
01:15:03,550 --> 01:15:06,910
Oh, no, no, no.
That's, uh, uh, fine.

973
01:15:06,990 --> 01:15:11,670
Oh, please. An American without
ice in his drink is unthinkable...

974
01:15:11,750 --> 01:15:14,350
if not unconstitutional.

975
01:15:56,150 --> 01:15:58,430
Nice boy.

976
01:15:58,470 --> 01:16:01,550
Goodboy.

977
01:16:01,630 --> 01:16:04,310
Nice dog.

978
01:16:10,150 --> 01:16:13,430
Stay. Stay.

979
01:16:15,550 --> 01:16:18,070
Good boy.

980
01:16:22,470 --> 01:16:25,630
Stupid animal.

981
01:16:26,830 --> 01:16:30,310
It's absolutely dynamite.

982
01:16:30,390 --> 01:16:32,630
It could be our biggest
book of the year.

983
01:16:34,750 --> 01:16:38,830
Although, uh, I still want to
see the last chapter, of course.

984
01:16:38,870 --> 01:16:43,110
I happen to have it right in my
pocket. Finished it this morning.

985
01:16:43,190 --> 01:16:48,150
- Splendid. I'm sure I shan't
be disappointed. - Cheers.

986
01:16:48,190 --> 01:16:50,230
Cheers.

987
01:16:55,110 --> 01:16:58,110
Mr. Westlake, you probably
won't see me again.

988
01:16:58,190 --> 01:17:01,350
I've given someone
a power of attorney...

989
01:17:01,430 --> 01:17:04,870
to get in touch with you
regarding contracts and payments.

990
01:17:04,950 --> 01:17:10,070
Under the circumstances, your absence
will probably be our best publicity.

991
01:17:10,150 --> 01:17:12,950
You're at considerable risk,
aren't you?

992
01:17:13,030 --> 01:17:16,630
Well, if you publish this, you're
going to be taking a risk yourself.

993
01:17:16,710 --> 01:17:21,150
We've dealt with controversy
before. The spice of life.

994
01:17:21,230 --> 01:17:26,430
These fellows don't play by the
Marquis of Queen... It-It is Marquis?

995
01:17:26,510 --> 01:17:29,470
- Yes, Marquis.
- Marquis of Queensbury rules, you know.

996
01:17:29,550 --> 01:17:32,390
Well, I certainly hope not.
Not half so much fun.

997
01:17:43,190 --> 01:17:45,190
You wait here.

998
01:18:04,630 --> 01:18:06,590
Mr. Westlake, I'm terribly sorry.
These gentlemen...

999
01:18:06,630 --> 01:18:08,710
- It's about the Kendig manuscript.
- That's all right.

1000
01:18:08,790 --> 01:18:11,230
- I've been looking forward to this.
- Good.

1001
01:18:11,270 --> 01:18:12,900
Glad you're not gonna try one of those

1002
01:18:12,935 --> 01:18:15,510
I-don't-know-what-
you're-talking-about stories.

1003
01:18:15,590 --> 01:18:17,950
My name is Parker Westlake.

1004
01:18:18,030 --> 01:18:20,470
- The point is...
- What's yours?

1005
01:18:20,550 --> 01:18:23,190
- What?
- What are your names?

1006
01:18:24,350 --> 01:18:26,310
Smith and Jones.

1007
01:18:26,350 --> 01:18:30,070
From my reading ofthe manuscript,
you have to be Myerson.

1008
01:18:30,150 --> 01:18:33,710
Are you Joe Cutter, by any chance?
I'm glad to meet you.

1009
01:18:33,790 --> 01:18:37,990
Now, please, why don't we sit down
and reason this thing together?

1010
01:18:38,070 --> 01:18:41,630
Why don't you give us the
manuscript? You can't publish it.

1011
01:18:41,710 --> 01:18:44,030
I think you're wrong about that.

1012
01:18:48,150 --> 01:18:50,750
Tell him, Joe.

1013
01:18:50,830 --> 01:18:53,390
I'm afraid he's right.

1014
01:18:53,470 --> 01:18:57,750
I don't like to make threats.
They sound foolish in the daylight.

1015
01:18:57,830 --> 01:19:00,870
But I am to infer that if I
don't give you the manuscript...

1016
01:19:00,950 --> 01:19:03,430
you'll creep in here
one dark night and take it.

1017
01:19:03,510 --> 01:19:06,910
Oris it more along
the lines of, uh...

1018
01:19:06,990 --> 01:19:11,350
if you don't cooperate with us,
we'll set off bombs in your offices?

1019
01:19:11,390 --> 01:19:13,590
You said it, we didn't.

1020
01:19:13,670 --> 01:19:16,230
Gentlemen, let me
tell you something.

1021
01:19:16,310 --> 01:19:18,204
I think this is one of the most exciting

1022
01:19:18,205 --> 01:19:20,430
literary properties
I've seen in a long time.

1023
01:19:20,510 --> 01:19:23,070
It simply isn't possible
for you to suppress it.

1024
01:19:23,150 --> 01:19:26,910
Let me caution you. I've run
off copies of the manuscript...

1025
01:19:26,990 --> 01:19:28,910
and had them put
in safe places.

1026
01:19:28,990 --> 01:19:33,150
So even if I suffer
an unfortunate accident...

1027
01:19:33,230 --> 01:19:36,030
the process of publication
will continue.

1028
01:19:36,110 --> 01:19:39,750
Naturally, we don't intend to
use our usual printing house.

1029
01:19:39,830 --> 01:19:42,110
So no one will know
where the book is...

1030
01:19:42,190 --> 01:19:45,990
until it's far too late tostop
its distribution to the bookshops.

1031
01:19:46,030 --> 01:19:49,110
I think your friend Kendig...

1032
01:19:49,190 --> 01:19:52,430
has you well and truly
by the short hairs.

1033
01:19:55,630 --> 01:19:58,270
If you publish that book, you're
signing his death warrant.

1034
01:19:58,350 --> 01:20:01,110
There's only one man who can stop
the publication of that book...

1035
01:20:01,190 --> 01:20:03,310
and that's Kendig himself.

1036
01:20:03,390 --> 01:20:05,470
Why don't you
talk to him about it?

1037
01:20:12,390 --> 01:20:14,770
- We can't find the bastard.
- Find him?

1038
01:20:14,815 --> 01:20:16,510
My dear fellow, where's
the difficulty in that?

1039
01:20:16,590 --> 01:20:19,790
He's staying right here in London
at the Windsor Hotel.

1040
01:20:19,870 --> 01:20:22,830
- What?
- The Windsor Hotel in Landcaster Gate...

1041
01:20:22,870 --> 01:20:25,110
just north ofthe park.

1042
01:20:27,110 --> 01:20:29,110
Thank you.

1043
01:20:54,710 --> 01:20:59,270
Room 416. Apparently,
he's expecting us.

1044
01:21:03,670 --> 01:21:06,110
We'll take the stairs.

1045
01:21:07,790 --> 01:21:11,070
- How'd you get here?
- He telephoned my embassy.

1046
01:21:11,110 --> 01:21:13,870
- He's very democratic, isn't he?
- Yes, isn't he?

1047
01:21:13,950 --> 01:21:17,990
I do like him, you know.
One can't help it.

1048
01:21:37,390 --> 01:21:39,470
Come on.
He's not gonna shoot you.

1049
01:21:40,510 --> 01:21:42,510
Shh.

1050
01:21:43,870 --> 01:21:46,070
Kendig?

1051
01:22:26,510 --> 01:22:28,510
Close the door.

1052
01:22:42,790 --> 01:22:44,870
So he's expecting us, huh?

1053
01:22:46,630 --> 01:22:48,630
Hello, boys.

1054
01:22:49,870 --> 01:22:52,070
Thanks for coming.

1055
01:22:52,150 --> 01:22:54,870
Why don't you sit down?
Make yourselves comfortable.

1056
01:22:54,950 --> 01:22:58,110
Joe, give everyone
a drink, will ya?

1057
01:22:58,150 --> 01:23:00,710
Whiskey is right there
next to the tape recorder...

1058
01:23:00,790 --> 01:23:04,190
and there's some ice,
ifit hasn't melted by this time.

1059
01:23:04,270 --> 01:23:08,190
Sorry there's no vodka, Yaskov.
I simply forgot it.

1060
01:23:08,230 --> 01:23:12,710
- Myerson, couldn't find
any bourbon and coke.

1061
01:23:12,790 --> 01:23:15,430
I suppose you're
wondering where I am.

1062
01:23:16,910 --> 01:23:19,230
Well, we know I'm not
about to try the airports...

1063
01:23:19,270 --> 01:23:22,070
the boat-trains
and the liners in Southampton...

1064
01:23:22,150 --> 01:23:25,830
the trains to Scotland
and the ferryboats to Ireland.

1065
01:23:25,910 --> 01:23:28,750
Did you think of Ireland, Joe,
or did you slip up on that one?

1066
01:23:28,830 --> 01:23:30,910
We thought of it.

1067
01:23:30,950 --> 01:23:35,030
Well, I'll give you a clue
as to my whereabouts later on.

1068
01:23:35,110 --> 01:23:38,710
In the meanwhile, the reason I
asked you all to come up here...

1069
01:23:38,790 --> 01:23:42,950
is 'cause I want you to pick up
a copy of my last chapter.

1070
01:23:43,030 --> 01:23:46,350
It's sitting on top
ofthe chest of drawers...

1071
01:23:46,430 --> 01:23:49,350
right next to the recorder.

1072
01:23:49,430 --> 01:23:51,470
That's all. Why don't you
take it home and read it?

1073
01:23:51,550 --> 01:23:53,830
Enjoy yourselves.
Have a good time.

1074
01:23:53,910 --> 01:23:57,310
Thanks very much for coming,
and, uh, good night.

1075
01:23:58,990 --> 01:24:01,710
Shit.

1076
01:24:17,230 --> 01:24:19,350
- Good night.
- Good night.

1077
01:24:23,350 --> 01:24:25,470
- Good night, Joe.
- Yep.

1078
01:25:14,870 --> 01:25:18,150
Good grief, Joe,
you look terrible.

1079
01:25:18,190 --> 01:25:21,470
Well, you've been keeping me
up past my regular bedtime.

1080
01:25:21,550 --> 01:25:24,710
Mm. Chair, please.

1081
01:25:26,750 --> 01:25:31,030
- Myerson thrown in the towel yet?
- He wants to see you dead.

1082
01:25:31,070 --> 01:25:35,470
Oh, it doesn't make any difference
whether I'm dead or alive, Joe.

1083
01:25:35,510 --> 01:25:37,750
He's all washed up now.
Doesn't he know that?

1084
01:25:37,830 --> 01:25:41,430
Lean forward, please.
Hands behind your back.

1085
01:25:41,510 --> 01:25:43,870
- How come he hasn't quit yet?
- He's a little bit like you.

1086
01:25:43,950 --> 01:25:48,390
- He won't quit until he gets even.
- Should be even by now.

1087
01:25:48,430 --> 01:25:51,790
He tried to emasculate me,
and I retaliated.

1088
01:25:53,390 --> 01:25:55,590
- What's your game plan now?
- There isn't any. The game's over.

1089
01:25:55,670 --> 01:25:57,990
It's all finished.
I've had my fun.

1090
01:25:58,030 --> 01:26:01,230
- It's too late for that.
I've got my orders. -Ahh.

1091
01:26:01,270 --> 01:26:06,230
I understand, Joe. You'll never
see me again after tonight.

1092
01:26:06,270 --> 01:26:08,270
- I'll find ya.
- No.

1093
01:26:08,350 --> 01:26:10,510
Did you pick up
my last, uh, chapter?

1094
01:26:10,590 --> 01:26:12,990
Yes, I did. And I think
you went a little bit too far.

1095
01:26:13,070 --> 01:26:16,470
- Oh, I don't think so.
- You know, I don't understand you.

1096
01:26:16,550 --> 01:26:18,830
It's not like you to paint
yourself into a corner.

1097
01:26:18,910 --> 01:26:21,310
But I don't see where
you've got any back door.

1098
01:26:21,390 --> 01:26:24,270
- You're my back door, Joe.
- I can't do you any favors.

1099
01:26:24,350 --> 01:26:27,630
- Sure you can. You already did.
- I did?

1100
01:26:27,710 --> 01:26:30,990
You know I'd never use this.
You didn't do anything about it.

1101
01:26:32,230 --> 01:26:34,950
I'm gonna have to put
a gag in your mouth, Joe.

1102
01:26:35,030 --> 01:26:37,870
The cleaning lady will
turn you loose in the morning.

1103
01:26:37,910 --> 01:26:41,230
- I hope she's pretty.
- Open your mouth.

1104
01:27:00,230 --> 01:27:04,990
Oh, uh, you can call
your crowd off the airport.

1105
01:27:05,030 --> 01:27:07,590
I've got a little plane
on the coast near Beachy Head.

1106
01:27:07,670 --> 01:27:10,750
I'll be taking off first thing
in the morning across the Channel.

1107
01:27:16,470 --> 01:27:19,150
No bullets.
I'm proud of you, Joe.

1108
01:28:16,070 --> 01:28:19,430
- Yeah?
- Hello?

1109
01:28:19,470 --> 01:28:21,790
- Hello?
- Hello?

1110
01:28:21,870 --> 01:28:26,230
Joe Cutter is tied to a chair
in his room.

1111
01:28:26,310 --> 01:28:28,830
You'd better cut him loose.

1112
01:28:28,910 --> 01:28:31,110
What? Who is this?

1113
01:28:31,190 --> 01:28:33,950
This is Eleanor Roosevelt.

1114
01:28:35,190 --> 01:28:38,590
What? Who is...

1115
01:28:38,630 --> 01:28:40,630
Hello?

1116
01:28:55,510 --> 01:28:58,110
- Hello.
- Hello, Is? Did you make it?

1117
01:28:58,190 --> 01:29:00,510
No. No, I didn't make it.

1118
01:29:00,550 --> 01:29:04,110
This is a recording of
a person asleep. How are you?

1119
01:29:04,150 --> 01:29:08,270
Right on schedule.
As of now, the clock is running.

1120
01:29:08,350 --> 01:29:11,830
- Well, where is it running?
- The Pond Gemington.

1121
01:29:11,910 --> 01:29:13,830
The Pond where?

1122
01:29:13,910 --> 01:29:16,790
The Pond, near that
beautiful graveyard.

1123
01:29:16,830 --> 01:29:19,510
You know, the one
with the Norman church.

1124
01:29:19,590 --> 01:29:24,110
And all those cold stones. Yes, yes, I
remember. I'll see you there in an hour.

1125
01:29:38,190 --> 01:29:40,190
Damn it!

1126
01:30:00,270 --> 01:30:02,350
Police. Thank God.

1127
01:30:02,430 --> 01:30:05,070
You fellas are never supposed
to be around when you're needed.

1128
01:30:05,150 --> 01:30:08,630
- Having a spot of trouble, sir?
- Yeah. I got a flat tire there.

1129
01:30:08,710 --> 01:30:11,750
I just made a telephone call,
came back, tire was flat...

1130
01:30:11,830 --> 01:30:14,470
- and there's no spare in there.
- Your car, sir?

1131
01:30:14,550 --> 01:30:18,230
- No, it's a rental. - Well, that's
where the spare should be, sir.

1132
01:30:18,310 --> 01:30:20,830
Yeah, but it's not there.

1133
01:30:22,470 --> 01:30:25,310
Listen, superspy, I wouldn't tell
Myerson about this if I were you.

1134
01:30:25,390 --> 01:30:28,870
- Fuck, Myerson.
- Oh, by the way, did he get your passport?

1135
01:30:31,270 --> 01:30:34,790
- Where you from in America, sir?
- Flagstaff, Arizona.

1136
01:30:34,870 --> 01:30:38,470
Hey, is there a place around here I can
rent a car? I got to get to Eastbourne.

1137
01:30:38,550 --> 01:30:41,230
Well, it might be a bit difficult
at this time of the morning, sir.

1138
01:30:41,310 --> 01:30:44,870
Why don't you come back to the station
and wait for one ofthe garages to open?

1139
01:30:44,950 --> 01:30:47,070
We'll make you
a nice cup of coffee.

1140
01:30:49,270 --> 01:30:54,830
We'll be at the Lambath heliport
in 15 or 20 minutes. Right.

1141
01:30:54,910 --> 01:30:57,270
If he doesn't take off before
daylight, we mightjust catch him.

1142
01:30:57,350 --> 01:31:00,030
-What time is daylight?
- About 7:00. It's 6:15 now.

1143
01:31:00,110 --> 01:31:02,590
- Is a cab waiting for us downstairs?
-Yes, sir.

1144
01:31:34,510 --> 01:31:37,870
- Now I want to know...
- I owe him one.

1145
01:31:37,910 --> 01:31:40,590
This is the quid pro quo, right?

1146
01:31:48,430 --> 01:31:50,350
I'm in a little bit
of a hurry, sir.

1147
01:31:50,430 --> 01:31:52,990
Um, is there any chance of
getting an all-night taxi service...

1148
01:31:53,070 --> 01:31:56,310
from Brighton or Seaford
or one of those places?

1149
01:31:56,390 --> 01:32:00,790
Here, Sarge, didn't old Tony Cosgrove
used to run some sort of taxi service?

1150
01:32:00,830 --> 01:32:04,270
- Yeah. If he's still alive.
- He's still alive, all right.

1151
01:32:04,350 --> 01:32:07,350
Give him a go, Harry. We'll
have you away in no time, sir.

1152
01:32:07,430 --> 01:32:09,750
Thank you very much.
Sure appreciate it.

1153
01:32:11,230 --> 01:32:13,670
Now, let's see.
Tony Cosgrove.

1154
01:32:27,070 --> 01:32:29,110
This time we'll
get there before him.

1155
01:32:29,190 --> 01:32:31,830
He'll never expect us
to get a copter up.

1156
01:32:31,910 --> 01:32:35,910
- You could be right.
- You bet your fucking ass I'm right.

1157
01:32:39,150 --> 01:32:42,270
Straight along the A-20.
How long do you think you'll be?

1158
01:32:42,350 --> 01:32:44,990
- Oh, about half an hour.
- It'll be about 30 minutes, sir.

1159
01:32:45,070 --> 01:32:47,550
Excuse me, sir, but what
did you say your name was?

1160
01:32:47,630 --> 01:32:51,710
- Burton. Henry Burton.
- Oh, yes, that's right. Thank you, sir.

1161
01:32:51,790 --> 01:32:54,430
I wonder if you could show me
some means of identification?

1162
01:32:54,510 --> 01:33:00,270
- Sure. You want a passport?
Driver's license? - Either, sir.

1163
01:33:02,190 --> 01:33:04,150
- There.
- Thank you.

1164
01:33:10,350 --> 01:33:13,270
You do rather look
a bit like this chap, sir.

1165
01:33:13,350 --> 01:33:16,390
But I'm sure it had nothing to do
with you. Just a coincidence, eh?

1166
01:33:17,590 --> 01:33:19,510
We've had a bulletin, you see.

1167
01:33:19,590 --> 01:33:22,510
An American that you rather
resemble is wanted for questioning.

1168
01:33:24,750 --> 01:33:26,750
Hmm.

1169
01:33:26,830 --> 01:33:29,950
Well, I guess I look like
everybody and his brother.

1170
01:33:30,030 --> 01:33:33,710
What has this, uh...
What is this fellow wanted for?

1171
01:33:33,750 --> 01:33:37,950
Oh, nothing in particular. Just some people
would like to ask him a few questions.

1172
01:33:39,230 --> 01:33:41,790
Oh, what the hell's going on
here with the lights?

1173
01:34:45,430 --> 01:34:49,430
- Oh, hi, there. - Morning. When
did you join the police force?

1174
01:34:49,510 --> 01:34:52,830
- It's the only car I could find that
had any gas in it. - Good thinking.

1175
01:34:52,910 --> 01:34:56,030
Listen, no matterwhat happens,
you stay put right here.

1176
01:34:56,110 --> 01:34:58,550
- I'll be back within an hour, okay?
- Okay.

1177
01:34:58,630 --> 01:35:00,698
And if you're not back
within the hour, I'll wait

1178
01:35:00,699 --> 01:35:02,950
for another hour
and another and another...

1179
01:37:04,670 --> 01:37:07,750
Follow him!

1180
01:39:47,230 --> 01:39:49,990
Jesus!

1181
01:39:50,070 --> 01:39:52,790
Wow! I guess that
takes care of Mr. Kendig.

1182
01:39:52,830 --> 01:39:54,910
That takes
care of him, all right.

1183
01:39:54,990 --> 01:39:57,510
The son of a bitch is down there
in that undertow in 47 pieces.

1184
01:39:59,510 --> 01:40:01,510
The son of a gun
is dead finally.

1185
01:40:03,310 --> 01:40:05,710
The son of a bitch
better stay dead.

1186
01:40:08,030 --> 01:40:11,110
Pity. I shall miss him.

1187
01:40:42,790 --> 01:40:45,710
- Everything go okay?
- Fine.

1188
01:40:45,750 --> 01:40:49,030
Good.

1189
01:40:49,110 --> 01:40:53,710
- Um, South of France for two
weeks? - Sounds okay. - Good.

1190
01:41:17,430 --> 01:41:20,990
I hope this book is half
as exciting as they say it is.

1191
01:41:21,070 --> 01:41:24,430
Oh, it is. Fourteen weeks, number
one on the best seller list.

1192
01:41:24,510 --> 01:41:27,390
Oh, how marvelous.

1193
01:41:27,430 --> 01:41:31,470
They say he was murdered
by his own men, the C. I. A.

1194
01:41:31,550 --> 01:41:33,630
Do you think there's
any truth in that?

1195
01:41:33,710 --> 01:41:38,030
There are those who say he's
still alive, living in Australia.

1196
01:41:38,070 --> 01:41:41,270
Oh, really?
Oh, is that a fact...

1197
01:41:46,150 --> 01:41:48,430
This is indefensible.

1198
01:41:48,510 --> 01:41:51,790
You must stop
these ridiculous charades.

1199
01:41:51,870 --> 01:41:55,310
The agency thinks you are dead.

1200
01:41:55,390 --> 01:41:59,270
No one, with the possible exception
of me, gives a damn about you.

1201
01:41:59,350 --> 01:42:01,990
If you do not stop
these absurd disguises...

1202
01:42:02,070 --> 01:42:04,830
I will personally rip
that beard from your chin...

1203
01:42:04,910 --> 01:42:07,830
and scream "fire"
at the top of myvoice.

1204
01:42:07,870 --> 01:42:10,070
Okay, okay.
You madeyour point.

1205
01:42:10,150 --> 01:42:14,670
Good. How'd you like to play
some gin this evening?

1206
01:42:14,750 --> 01:42:17,630
- For how much?
- Will you never learn?

